<main id="main">
  <header>
    <br>
  <h1 id="title">Maurizia Aldeiturriaga</h1>
    <h2>- Legendary tambourine player -</h2>
  <div id="img-div">
    <figure>
      <img id="image" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/49/Maurizia.jpg" alt="Maurizia Aldaiturriaga" class="center black-border">      
      <figcaption id="img-caption">Maurizia Aldeiturriaga</figcaption>
      <br>
    </figure>
    </header>
    <div id="tribute-info" class="container">      
      <div class="item1"></div>
      <div class="item2>">
        <p>Maurizia was a famous tambourine player, who was born in 1904 in Zeberio Bizkaia, Basque Country). Maurizia is one of those women that was become visible in men world.  </p>       
        <p>The most significant aspect of her actuations was her capacity of improvisation when composing couplets and her special voice.</p>
        <p>Althoug, tambourine is a classical basque music instrument, the influence of Maurizia is visible also in different expressions of basque culture. The most known example is the Kortatu's song "Tolosa Ihauteriak": the voice of Maurizia can be heared in that song.</p>
        <p>Here is a summary of the time line of Maurizia's life:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>1904:</strong> Maurizia was born in Zeberio (Bizkaia, Basque Country)</li><br>
          <li><strong>1913:</strong> She was sent out to work as a maid when she was just 9-years-old, as usual at that time.  </li><br>
          <li><strong>1927:</strong> She was married with Benantzio Bernaola, who was her artistic partner.</li><br>
          <li><strong>1936:</strong> Civil war and the next years were specially hard times for them.</li><br>
          <li><strong>1985:</strong> "Euskal Herriko soinu tresnak" record was published.</li><br>
          <li><strong>1988:</strong> She died at the age of 83. </li><br>
          <li><strong>1998:</strong> "Alboka eta trikitixa" record was published.</li><br>
        </ul>
        <p> Click here to view more about <a id="tribute-link" href="https://eu.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurizia_Aldeiturriaga" target="_blank" >Maurizia Aldeiturriaga</a> </p>
      </div>          
      <div class="item3"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
